crates/ctx-cage/tests/ is the integration and unit test suite for ctx-cage's process-sandboxing broker, its `bwrap` argv builder, wire protocol, HTTP-rewriting proxy, and CLI mode resolution. Depending on it as a reader one level up means: these are the executable specification of the sandbox's security- and correctness-critical contracts (bind mounts, DNS fallback avoidance, secret masking, error-channel routing) — changes to those subsystems must keep these tests green or the ADRs they encode (ADR-046, ADR-049) are being violated.

Shared coupling: `broker_loopback.rs`, `protocol.rs`, and `proxy.rs` all exercise real or in-memory transports (UnixListener/UnixStream, byte buffers, socketpairs) rather than mocking the wire format directly, so a change to `ctx_cage::protocol`'s frame format must be validated against all three. `bwrap_build.rs` and `cage_assets.rs` both encode ADR-049's DNS-hang-avoidance rule (resolv.conf must be bound and must contain a non-loopback nameserver) — the two must be updated together if the resolv.conf handling strategy changes. `common/mod.rs` supplies the only fixtures (`BwrapConfig`, `ClaudeBinds`) shared across bwrap-related tests; changing its fixture shapes ripples into `bwrap_build.rs`.

Per-file roles: `broker_loopback.rs` drives the broker end-to-end via a `FakeSpawner`; `bwrap_build.rs` is pure argv-construction verification; `bwrap_discover.rs` covers crate-dir discovery; `cage_assets.rs` guards embedded resolv.conf content; `cli.rs` is pure flag-to-Mode logic; `protocol.rs` is pure frame-format round-tripping; `proxy.rs` covers header rewriting and the stderr-must-never-be-touched invariant for interactive PTY safety; `summarize.rs` covers stale-doc detection helpers.

Subtree-spanning invariant: every test using real filesystem/socket paths (broker_loopback, bwrap_discover, proxy) generates unique paths via PID + atomic counter to survive parallel test execution; none rely on `Drop`-based cleanup, so panics can leak tempfiles.

No intent.md exists to check divergence against.